definition.value: A cephalosporin carboxylic acid anion having a 7beta-[(2R)-2-amino-2-(4-hydroxyphenyl)acetyl]amino side-chain, formed by proton loss from the carboxy group of the cephalosporin cefadroxil.

A cephalosporin carboxylic acid anion having acetoxymethyl and [2-(2-amino-1,3-thiazol-4-yl)-2-(methoxyimino)acetyl]amino side-groups, formed by proton loss from the carboxy group of the cephalosporin cefotaxime.
An acrylate macromolecule composed of repeating 1-methyl-1-[(oxiran-2-ylmethoxy)carbonyl]ethylene units.
A macromolecule composed of repeating 2,7-diethenyl-9H-carbazole units.
A macromolecule containing alternating arylene and ethynylene repeating units.
A polymer composed of repeating 1-ethynylnaphthalene units.

An organic sodium salt that is the nmonosodium salt of ceftazidime, a cephalosporin having 7beta-[(2Z)-2-(2-amino-1,3-thiazol-4-yl)-2-{[(2-carboxypropan-2-yl)oxy]imino}acetyl]amino and 3-pyridinium-1-ylmethyl side-groups.

A cephalosporin carboxylic acid anion formed by proton loss from the carboxy group of ceftazidime, a cephalosporin having 7beta-[(2Z)-2-(2-amino-1,3-thiazol-4-yl)-2-{[(2-carboxypropan-2-yl)oxy]imino}acetyl]amino and 3-pyridinium-1-ylmethyl side-groups.
A chloroamino acid comprising a tyrosine core with a chloro- substituent ortho to the phenolic hydroxy group.
An L-tyrosine derivative in which an L-tyrosine core has two chloro substituents at each position ortho to the benzyl hydroxy group and an acetyl substituent on the nitrogen atom.
A dihydroxyflavanone that is pinocembrin substituted by a prenyl group at position 8.
An L-tyrosine derivative which has two halogeno-substituents on the benzyl moiety.
A macromolecule that contain both neutral and charged repeating units.
An ionomer macromolecule formed by incorporating perfluorovinyl ether groups terminated with sulfonate groups onto a tetrafluoroethylene (Teflon) backbone.
A macromolecule containing exclusively silicon atoms in the backbone.
A macromolecule composed of repeating dimethylsilane units.
A derivative of p-salicylic acid with chloro- substituents at C-3 and C-5 of the benzene ring.
The conjugate base of 3,5-dichlorohydroxybenzoic acid. Comprising a 3,5-dihydroxybenzoic acid core with the carboxylic acid proton missing, giving a charge of -1.
A galactotetraose composed of four beta-D-galactose units joined by (1->4)-linkages.
A derivative of beta-D-glucuronic acid in which a methyl group is present at the anomeric position.
A macromolecule having many branched main chains attached to the backbone.
A member of the class of  hydroxyisoflavans that is (R)-isoflavan substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 2' and 4' and a 2,2-dimethyl-2H-pyran group across positions 7 and 8 respectively.
A linear trisaccharide comprising D-glucuronic acid, D-galacturonic acid and L-rhamnose residues, linked sequentially (1->3) and (1->2).

A member of the class of benzoic acids that is benzoic acid having iodo substituents at the 2-, 4- and 6-positions and acetamido substituents at the 3- and 5-positions. It is used, mainly as its N-methylglucamine and sodium salts, as an X-ray contrast medium in gastrointestinal studies, angiography, and urography.

The sodium salt of a benzoic acid having iodo substituents at the 2-, 4- and 6-positions and acetamido substituents at the 3- and 5-positions. It is used, often as a mixture with the meglumine salt, as an X-ray contrast medium in gastrointestinal studies, angiography, and urography.
An iodoamino acid that is L-histidine in which the imidazole ring is substituted by iodine at positions  2- and 5(4).
An iodoamino acid that is L-histidine derivative in which the imidazole ring is substituted by iodine at position 5.
A diblock copolymer composed of adjacent blocks of poly(methyl acrylate) and deuterated polystyrene.
The disodium salt of L-tyrosine.
An L-tyrosine derivative having a 4-arsonophenyldiazenyl group at the 3-position of the benzene ring.
A C-nitro compound comprising hexanoic acid with a (2,4-dinitrophenyl)amino substituent at position C-6.
An organoheteryl group consisting of arsonophenyl attached to diazene at the 4-position and having the beta-nitrogen as the point of attachment.
A quinoline derivative with a 1,3-dioxoindan-2-yl substituent at C-2.
A penicilloyl group formed from nucleophilic cleavage of the beta-lactam ring of benzylpenicillin.
A penicilloyl group formed from nucleophilic cleavage of the beta-lactam ring of phenoxymethylpenicillin.
A penicilloyl group formed from nucleophilic cleavage of the beta-lactam ring of ampicillin.
A penicilloyl group formed from nucleophilic cleavage of the beta-lactam ring of amoxicillin.
The acyl group formed from phenoxymethylpenicillin.
A polymer macromolecule composed of repeating substituted or unsubstituted methanimine units.
A macromolecule composed of repeating methanimine units.
A poly(ethylene glycol) derivative that is poly(ethylene glycol) in which one of the terminal hydroxy groups has been acylated by formal condensation with methacrylic acid.
A quassinoid with formula C25H34O10. It is a natural product isolated from several plant species and exhibits anti-cancer and anti-malarial properties.
A macromolecule composed of a main chain containing a sequence of conjugated multiple bonds.
A compound comprising six covalently linked L-lysine residues ionically bound to hydrogen bromide.
The acyl group formed from amoxicillin.
The acyl group formed from ampicillin.
A macromolecule composed of repeating methyl (2S)-2-[(2S)-2-(methylideneamino)propanamido]propanoate units.
A triblock copolymer composed of a central polybutadiene chain flanked on each side by polystyrene chains.
